  "prompt": "Do all jobs in science require chemistry and physics? What if I just like biology?",
  "response": "Not all jobs in science require a strong background in chemistry and physics, but many scientific fields are interdisciplinary and may incorporate concepts from these areas. If you have a strong interest in biology, there are many career paths you can pursue that may focus primarily on biological sciences. Here are a few examples:\n\n1. **Biology**: Careers in ecology, microbiology, botany, or zoology can focus mainly on biological concepts.\n\n2. **Molecular Biology and Genetics**: While they may intersect with chemistry, these fields focus more on the biological processes at the molecular level.\n\n3. **Healthcare Professions**: Careers such as nursing, physical therapy, or occupational therapy primarily emphasize biological and life sciences.\n\n4. **Environmental Science**: While some aspects may involve chemistry and physics, many roles primarily focus on biology, conservation, and ecology.\n\n5. **Biotechnology**: This field often combines biology with technology but can focus on biological applications.\n\n6. **Education**: If you're interested in teaching, you can focus on biology and educate the next generation about life sciences.\n\nWhile a basic understanding of chemistry and physics can enhance your knowledge in biology, you can definitely carve out a successful career focused primarily on your interests in biology. Always consider the specific requirements of the career paths you're interested in, as some may require at least foundational coursework in chemistry or physics.",
